data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_03cb0ad4f1f7d5060069b346c6ca10819093a600716c5b957d","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":186,"text":"Below is what makes Centralia, Pennsylvania so remarkable — drawing from the latest online accounts and authoritative sources:\n\nCentralia’s claim to fame is—or rather *infamy*—its underground coal fire, intentionally started in 1962 but still burning beneath the town today. What was once a cleanup of a municipal dump inadvertently ignited a coal seam below, and the fire spread into a vast web of abandoned mine shafts stretching for miles. Having persisted for over six decades, it’s considered one of the longest-burning coal fires in American history ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia_mine_fire)).\n\nBecause of the fire, Centralia transformed—almost overnight—from a once-thriving coal-mining borough into a near-ghost town. In 1980, about 1,000 people still lived there; by the 2020 census, that number had dropped to just five residents ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania)). Centralia now stands as the *least-populated municipality in Pennsylvania* ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania)).\n\nEfforts to extinguish the fire were attempted early on but ultimately failed. Engineers tried flooding mine shafts, pumping in inert materials, and isolating burning sections—none succeeded. The reasons? A sprawling subsurface network of mine tunnels, plenty of remaining fuel in the coal seams, and consistent access to oxygen via cracks and ruptures in the earth’s surface ([factumobscura.com](https://www.factumobscura.com/in-depth/centralia-pennsylvania-the-underground-mine-fire-that-refuses-to-die/)). Today, scientists estimate the fire could continue burning for more than a century ([sickhistory.com](https://sickhistory.com/centralia-pennsylvania-underground-fire-ghost-town/)).\n\nAs the surface deteriorated, many buildings were condemned and demolished, and in 1992 all real estate was seized by eminent domain ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania)). By 2002, the U.S. Postal Service revoked Centralia's ZIP code, basically erasing it from postal maps ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania)). A few determined residents held out in legal battles and eventually obtained the right—through a 2013 settlement—to remain in their homes until their deaths ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania)).\n\nOn the surface, the damage is eerie and cinematic. Cracked pavement, smoke rising from fissures, abandoned road segments like the infamous \"Graffiti Highway\"—covered in street art until it was buried under dirt in 2020 to deter trespassers ([uncoveringpa.com](https://uncoveringpa.com/visiting-centralia)). Nature, too, has stepped in: recent reports note that the burning town has become a curious habitat for wild plants and butterflies, as the once-industrial landscape slowly reclaims itself ([atlasobscura.com](https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/centralia-pennsylvania-rebirth)).\n\nCentralia also lives on in popular culture. It is widely believed to have inspired the setting for the 2006 horror film *Silent Hill*—its smoky roads and apocalyptic aura translating powerfully to the big screen ([factumobscura.com](https://www.factumobscura.com/in-depth/centralia-pennsylvania-the-underground-mine-fire-that-refuses-to-die/)).\n\nSumming up what makes Centralia extraordinary:\n- A subterranean coal fire that began accidentally in 1962 and still burns today.\n- Depleted population—down from thousands to just a handful of residents.\n- Government interventions: eminent domain, ZIP code removal, forced evacuations.\n- A visually haunting ghost town with smoking fissures, desolate roads, and poignant remnants of human habitation.\n- A site of growing interest for “dark tourism,” ecological rewilding, and pop-culture lore.\n\nSo what makes this place special is the combination of an unstoppable underground fire, an abandoned townscape, enduring human stories, and an ongoing transformation—both by nature and legend."}

